What is Prewalk?
Prewalk is a string interpolation tool into any text files. For example, latex source files, markdown files, or source code files of any programming languages. 
Though in the rest we focus on how to use Prewalk for markdown files in Gitbook projects. Some samples are also included for Katex and SVG in Gitbook.
Prerequisites
You need node.js and Gitbook cli installed.

Nodejs
GitbookCli

Node.js is required for Gitbook, not for Prewalk.
Prewalk's gitbook template includes Katex, a kind of Latex for web.
Notation
All jl.md files are your source files to be compliled into md files. For example:

test.jl.md
test.md

The same holds for jl.svg files.

test.jl.svg
test.svg

Here follows notations for important directories.

$InstallDir: the directory to install $Project.
$Project: the root directory of your projcect.
$Project/gitbook: put all your md and svg files here,
including Readme.md and SUMMARY.md.  


$Project/gitbook_out: Prewalk's output directory.
$Project/gitbook_out/_book: Gitbook's output directory.
$Project/jl: put all your julia source files here.
If you need own libraries.


$Project/prewalk: to customize Prewalk, edit files here.

How to install
The template for gitbook is in Prewalk/src/template/gitbookT
To generalte Gitbook template, open a julia REPL:
pkg> add Prewalk
julia> using Prewalk
julia> cd("$InstallDir")
julia> Prewalk.template("YOUR PROJECT NAME")
Back to the OS terminal.
$> cd $InstallDir/$Project
$> npm run serve
Open your browser at localhost:4000 by default.
Add md files
Suppose you want to add a new markdown file, "$Project/md/test.md". You need to create "$Project/md/test.jl.md". Put the following code in "test.jl.md".
### Hello world

ğŸ£| "Hello world" |ğŸ£
The special character,'ğŸ£', is called prewalkChar. You can type prewalkChar by:

Open julia REPL.
type "\:post_office:".
type TAB.

Although I like all default special chars, if you do not like some of default special chars, you can change it in "$Project//prewalk/julia/main.jl/module Conf:

prewalkChar
emptyChar
openChar
closeChar

The following command print these special chars.
 npm run chars
After compiling project files, we expect:
### Hello world

Hello world
Complile jl.md files
To compile all jl.md files, we run a script in $Project/package.json:
$> cd $Project
$> npm run build # It is Prewalk's build

# Followed by optional commands as follows.

$> npm run serve # gitbook serve gitbook_out
$> npm run build2 # gitbook build gitbook_out
Note that all jl.md files are compiled in the order decided by Julia's walkdir function. It implies that just one change in some jl.md file will require compiling all jl.md files.
More complex example
For $Project/.../test.jl.md, Prewalk evaluates julia code in the following order. Note that these files, 1 to 2, are not necessary. And all jl file is evaluated exactly once.

$Project/jl/user.jl
$Project/.../test.jl
$Project/.../test.jl.md

All jl.md file can contain multi line julia blcok between lines which only contain [# or #].
For the following code:
[#
x=10
#]

### Hello world

ğŸ£| "Hello world"*("!"^x) |ğŸ£
We expect:
### Hello world

Hello world!!!!!!!!!!
Line by line, Prewalk evaluates ğŸ£ as:

ğŸ£ğŸ£ to be replaced with the value of _default.
ğŸ£IDENTIFIER to be replaced with the value of IDENTIFIER.
ğŸ£| JULIA_EXPRESSION |ğŸ£ to be replaced with the value of JULIA_EXPRESSION.

Note that all replacement is done in terms of String. That is,"$(VALUE)".
For the following code:
[#
_default=123
#]

### Hello world

ğŸ£ğŸ£
We expect:
123
As special cases, if _default is an Iterator.Stateful or a function, the following code takes place of _default respectively:

popfirst!(default)
default()

[#
_default=Iterators.Stateful([1,2,3])
#]

### Hello world

Some typical errors
[#
x=1
y=(
  1
)
#]
It results an error because:

The first new line after "x=1" needs to be replaced with ";".
Contrally, the rest new lines after "y=(" are to be ignored.

To solve problems of this kind, you use a comment as follows.
[#
x=1
#
y=(
  1
)
#]
The following code also results an error because multi line comments are not supported.
[#
x=1
#=
SOME COMMENT
=#
y=(
  1
)
#]
Use JlWalk with Katex
Roughly speaking, all Katex expression is a latex expression between pairs of double dollar symbols. In the rest, we denote it as:

DoubleDollars latex_expression DoubleDollars

For the following code, where all "DoubleDollars" is to be replace with $$:
[#
exp1=collect(1:2:7)
exp2=collect(1:10)
exp1,exp2=[ "$(exp)"[2:end-1] for exp in [exp1,exp2]]
#]

DoubleDollars \{ ğŸ£|exp1|ğŸ£ \} \subset \{ ğŸ£|exp2|ğŸ£ \} DoubleDollars
